arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase VII: Roman mid CE 2nd c. collapse and repairs. A lead pipe is laid across the south at the foot of the Lower Temenos Retaining Wall. Collapse of the East Cryptoporticus and the addition of subterranean east west crosswalls between the stylobate walls supporting the East Triple Colonnade. The intentional deposition of earthen fill in these areas contains material dating to the to the CE 2nd c. Benches are installed in the West Cryptoporticus.
Bottom level of fill deposit between the east and west walls (Loci 28, 11) of the West Cryptoporticus East, just above the floor (Locus 25)
Center, from the North Balk of Locus 8 to the North end of Trench 97, 0.10-0.15 m above the floor (Locus 25).

This locus defines the lowest 0.10-to-0.15 m of fill above the surface of the West Cryptoporticus East floor (Locus 25). The fill throughout remained steadily around the range of Munsell Color 7.5 YR 5/4 Brown. It consisted of a combination of silt and sand, generally with a fine texture. It was compacted and had a moister feel to the touch than the fill found in upper levels. Locus 13 yielded many small finds, including a complete lamp (Seq. No. 97771), and numerous pieces of metal, both iron and bronze.

Phase VIII: Brief (?) period of abandonment marked by a thin layer of (largely) chocolate brown clean soil. A number of foundation elements are robbed out at this time including parts of the stylobates of the East and West Colonnades.
